[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The acceleration is happening right now. This isn\'t just sci-fi anymore. AI is already coming up with huge and completely new scientific discoveries and it\'s getting faster and faster. In the same week, we had not one but two papers published in nature, which is'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like the most prestigious scientific journal in the world. Both of them involve using AI to autonomously do scientific research. And this isn\'t just theory. These AI agents literally came up with new treatments for cancer,'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'blindness, antibiotic resistance, and other diseases that are currently really difficult to treat. And these breakthroughs are completely new. AI was able to come up with a ton of discoveries that human experts never'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thought of before. Most importantly, they actually work in real life. So, in this video, we\'re going to go over these two papers and why they\'re such a big deal. Now, this is super technical, but as always, I\'m going to simplify this to'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'make it easy to understand for everyone. Let\'s jump right in. All right, so the first paper is called accelerating scientific discovery with co-scientist and this is built by Google. This isn\'t just a regular AI chatbot. Co-scientist'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is fundamentally different and here\'s how it works. Instead of one huge model, it\'s actually an entire ecosystem of specialized AI agents working together. In fact, you can think of it as a'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'virtual lab. Here\'s how the agentic framework is organized. At the very top, you have the supervisor agent. This is the boss and its job is to take the goal specified by the human scientist, say a prompt like find a new way to treat this'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'specific type of leukemia. So, this supervisor agent parses that goal and then allocates tasks to the underlying agents. It\'s important to note that the supervisor is purely administrative. Its job is to ensure the system stays on'

[01:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'task. The actual creative ideation begins with the generation agent. This agent is tasked with brainstorming initial ideas. It goes out, explores the scientific literature using web search to pull in the latest and most relevant'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'data. Then it synthesizes existing findings into new proposed directions. Afterwards, it generates the initial batch of hypotheses or ideas. Now, usually when you\'re brainstorming,'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'especially in a complex field, the first few ideas you throw on the whiteboard are usually, well, terrible or highly flawed. So, this brings us to the next most critical component of the entire system, which is the reflection agent.'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Think of this agent as the most brutal rigorous reviewer you can possibly imagine. Its whole purpose is to try to destroy the hypotheses generated by the generation agent. Just tear them apart.'

[02:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It critically examines every proposed idea looking for flaws. It fact-checks to make sure everything is correct. It also checks for novelty, ensuring the idea isn\'t just a slight rephrasing of an existing discovery, but is actually a'

[02:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'new idea. So, the generation agent comes up with ideas and the reflection agent tries to tear them apart. The friction between these two agents is what elevates the system to produce really high-quality ideas. And then working'

[02:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'quietly in the background is the proximity agent. Its job is to map all these ideas out into a high-dimensional space to group similar ones together. So, if the generation comes up with several slightly different variations of'

[03:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pretty much the same thing, this proximity agent is able to detect this and then tell the system, "Hey, these are all essentially the same idea. Stop wasting compute and resources and move on to a different concept." process'

[03:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'doesn\'t stop there. Co-scientist also uses an evolution agent. This agent takes the harsh critiques from the reflection agent, looks at surviving ideas, and then iteratively refines'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'them. For example, it might take two good surviving ideas and mash them together to create a brilliant one. It tries to bridge logical gaps. Now, here\'s where it gets fascinating. How exactly does the system decide which of'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these surviving ideas is the best one? This is the genius part. The system uses a ranking agent to host an actual automated tournament of ideas. This is perhaps the most innovative aspect of'

[03:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the entire Co-Scientist architecture. The ranking agent uses an ELO rating system, just like in chess or in competitive video games, where if a lower ranked player manages to beat a'

[04:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'grandmaster, they get a huge chunk of their points. But if two equally ranked players tie, their scores barely move. It\'s the exact same mathematical principle, but applied to the rigorous evaluation of scientific ideas. And this'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Co-Scientist system actually simulates head-to-head debates between pairs of ideas. So, hypothesis A argues why it\'s more new or plausible or testable than hypothesis B, and hypothesis B tries to'

[04:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'argue back, pointing out flaws in hypothesis A. And then we have a separate AI model that acts as a judge, evaluating the debate. Winners gain ELO points, losers lose them. And over'

[04:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hundreds or even thousands of these automated simulated debates, the strongest and most robust ideas naturally rise to the top of the leaderboard. Now, if you\'ve been playing around with AI, you\'ll probably know'

[05:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that large language models are notorious for hallucinating and sometimes just making stuff up while sounding very confident. So, how do we know that Co-Scientist isn\'t just making up these ideas? How do we know it\'s actually'

[05:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'producing better and legit scientific hypotheses? Well, the researchers gave Co-Scientist 15 incredibly challenging unsolved biomedical goals written by PhD-level scientists, and they asked it'

[05:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to come up with the best solutions. They then asked human experts to provide their absolute best-guess solutions as well. They also gave the same goals to other state-of-the-art AI models at that time. And they asked independent human'

[05:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'experts to judge which ideas were better. Now, this is a blind test, so the human experts couldn\'t see if the ideas were generated by other humans or by which AI models, and the results were'

[05:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'remarkable. You can see that Co-Scientist, after giving it enough time to think and iterate, eventually beat all the AI models and the human experts. These independent human judges rated the ideas from Co-Scientist as'

[06:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'significantly higher in novelty, plausibility, and impact compared to the best solutions from human experts. So, this AI system, it\'s not just making stuff up. This is proof that it can'

[06:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually create new innovative ideas, which even independent human experts approve of. Now, generating solid ideas is one thing, but does this actually work in real life? That\'s the ultimate test. Well, next, the researchers did'

[06:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exactly that. They took the best outputs from Co-Scientist on some very different and incredibly complex problems that are not solved yet, and the results were astounding. Let\'s dive into each one.'

[06:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The first one involves acute myeloid leukemia, or AML for short. This is a very tough disease, and here\'s why it\'s so hard to cure. You see, acute myeloid leukemia is a devastating and highly'

[06:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'aggressive blood cancer that starts in the bone marrow. Now, the major challenge with AML isn\'t necessarily killing the cancer cells at the start. We actually have chemotherapies that can already do this quite well. The problem'

[07:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is that relapse is incredibly common, and when the disease does come back, it\'s highly resistant to the therapy. And it comes back really aggressively because of a specific subpopulation of the cells, which are called leukemia'

[07:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stem cells. These are deeply dormant cells that are like the roots of a weed. So, you can mow the lawn and kill the bulk of the cancer cells, but if you leave the roots, then the weeds grow back, and often stronger. So, these stem'

[07:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cells hide in the bone marrow, and they evade standard chemotherapy, and they could eventually cause a relapse. There\'s currently no good therapeutic solution for killing these dormant stem cells. Now, here\'s what the researchers'

[07:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'did. They handed Co-Scientist a massive dataset of 2,300 drugs that are already FDA approved for human use. They\'re just currently used for entirely different purposes. The prompt for the AI was'

[07:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'essentially, "Which of these 2,300 existing drugs could be repurposed to specifically fight acute myeloid leukemia?" Now, this is basically the entire field of drug repurposing. Designing a new drug from scratch would'

[08:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'almost take a decade and millions of dollars, and the failure rate is super high. But, if we can look at existing drugs and discover new uses for them, then it\'s a lot more efficient. Well, Co-Scientist actually found several'

[08:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'strong candidates. It identified drugs like binimetinib, pacritinib, and sorafenib. Let\'s take one example, binimetinib. This is currently approved and used for skin cancer. Not leukemia.'

[08:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But, they took the advice from Co-Scientist and tested binimetinib on leukemia cells in the lab, and it actually turned out to be extremely effective. It had an IC50 of 2'

[08:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'nanomolars against acute myeloid leukemia. Let\'s quickly clarify what this IC50 means. It\'s kind of a gold standard metric. So, this is a measure of a drug\'s potency. Specifically, how'

[09:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'much of a drug is needed to inhibit a biological process by exactly half. In this case, the process is the survival of the cancer cells. A lower number means the drug is very effective. You'

[09:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'need very little of it to do massive damage. And in this case, 2 nanomolars is an extremely low concentration. So, this indicates a very strong efficacy against those cancer cells. This shows'

[09:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that Co-Scientist isn\'t just a theoretical framework anymore. They\'ve already gotten it to find a new drug that works very well on a very problematic cancer that previously had no good therapies. Now, this benametinib'

[09:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is previously known to work for skin cancers, so maybe there\'s a connection there. But, here\'s another discovery that\'s even crazier. They told Co Scientist, "Don\'t just give us the obvious repurposing candidates. Give us'

[09:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some drugs that have no prior evidence linked to leukemia or cancer at all." They wanted completely new ideas that no human has ever published on this subject. And lo and behold, after a lot'

[10:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of thinking and internal debating and ranking different ideas, Co Scientist generated a hypothesis suggesting a drug called KIRA 6. Now, KIRA 6 is a fascinating molecule. It inhibits an'

[10:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'enzyme called IRE1 alpha, which manages cell stress. So, this decides how cells clear up misfolded or broken proteins. So, Co Scientist, after reading and synthesizing stuff across entirely'

[10:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'different fields of biology, hypothesized that targeting this specific stress pathway could selectively kill these leukemia cells. Humans have never thought of this'

[10:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'before. Now, let\'s dig into this a bit more. Why did the AI suggest there? Well, if you look into its hypothesis, the AI recognized that cancer cells, by their very nature of fast uncontrolled division, are also under huge internal'

[10:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stress because they\'re growing so fast. Their protein manufacturing machinery is running in overdrive and constantly breaking down. So, they rely heavily on this stress response pathway, like IRE1'

[11:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'alpha, just to survive their own chaos. It needs to constantly clean up a lot of broken proteins just to stay alive. Otherwise, the cell would just be filled with garbage. Co Scientist deduced that'

[11:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'if you inhibit this specific stress pathway with a drug, KIRA 6, this would mess up the cancer cells. Now, you might be wondering, "What about normal cells?" Well, it turns out that a normal healthy'

[11:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cell can tolerate this drug because it\'s not stressed. It doesn\'t really need to rely on this garbage pathway as often. But to the cancer cell, which is constantly dividing and under immense stress, this drug is very potent. At'

[11:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'least that\'s what the AI suggested. Of course, the next logical step is to test this in real life. So, the scientists applied this Curesix drug to these leukemia cells, and the results were'

[11:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shocking. It wasn\'t just good, it was remarkably effective. It turns out that Curesix was 18 times more effective at killing these leukemia stem cells. Again, these are the dreaded cells that cause the relapse of the cancer. These'

[12:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are the ones that previously had no good treatment, and they were very difficult to kill. But Co-scientist found that this drug was 18 times more effective at killing these types of cells compared to a normal healthy cell, which means it\'s'

[12:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a really effective and selective drug. Again, this is solid proof that AI isn\'t just making up ideas or spitting out known information anymore. Here, it actually output a new way to repurpose a'

[12:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'drug to treat a very difficult cancer. And this is a new method that human researchers have not thought of before. This is a genuine medical discovery. Now, beyond single drugs, the AI'

[12:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Co-scientist was also able to tackle combinations of drugs, which is actually really difficult. You see, one drug is just a single variable, but combining two drugs creates thousands of potential interactions to test for, including'

[12:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'effects and toxicity, and more. Introducing a third drug increases the possible combinations into the millions. Lab testing all these different components of drugs is pretty much impossible, but because this'

[13:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Co-scientist was able to synthesize all the information from the scientific literature out there, it\'s able to understand and predict these combinations a lot better than even the top human experts. So, again, targeting this specific type of leukemia, the AI I'

[13:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this combination of three drugs, JQ1, Olaparib, and MSA2. That was just its hypothesis, so again the researchers put this to the test in real life. And what'

[13:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they found is that this specific combination was indeed very effective against the cancer. Specifically, it works synergistically to attack the cancer from three different angles. The AI was correct in saying that these'

[13:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'three drugs together were significantly better at stopping the cancer than any of them were on their own. This is a huge deal because testing so many drug combinations is just economically and'

[13:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'physically impossible. There are millions of potential combinations, which is way too many for humans to test in real life through trial and error. But this breakthrough shows that we don\'t need millions of expensive lab'

[14:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'experiments. This AI can just synthesize all known information and come up with the best combinations on its own that actually work. This makes drug discovery way more efficient, especially for'

[14:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'combinations of drugs. So these are just a few examples of how you can get this AI agent system to find new treatments for a type of cancer that was very difficult to treat. But it doesn\'t just do cancer. If you want to supercharge'

[14:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your content, definitely check out Higgsfield, the sponsor of this video. Think of it as an all-in-one AI creation platform built specifically for creators. Instead of jumping between a bunch of different tools, Higgsfield'

[14:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'gives you access to some of the world\'s leading models in one place, including Seed Dance 2.0, Nano Banana, GPT Image 2, and more. What makes it really interesting is that Higgsfield also has its own tools built for full creative'

[15:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'workflows. For example, there\'s Higgsfield Supercomputer, which is basically a general-purpose AI super agent for content creation. You can give it one prompt and it can help with the whole process. Finding an idea, creating'

[15:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the product concept, writing the brand direction, generating the visuals, cutting the launch video, and even helping with distribution. And for actual video generation, Higgsfield has C Dance 2.0, which can generate 1080p'

[15:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'videos with synced audio. It also supports multiple inputs, so you can combine text, images, video clips, and audio references to control the final results more precisely. They also have'

[15:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Marketing Studio, which is really useful for making ads. You can paste a product link or upload a product image and it can generate multiple ad formats in one workflow, like UGC videos, tutorials, unboxings, product reviews, and more.'

[15:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'One product can instantly turn into a whole campaign. They also have Cinema Studio 3.5, which is built as a full end-to-end filmmaking pipeline. This is especially useful if you want more'

[16:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cinematic control. Instead of just typing a prompt and hoping it looks good, Cinema Studio is built around actual shot-level filmmaking. You can plan the scenes, control the camera, set the mood, add characters, and keep everything consistent across the whole'

[16:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'project. The big idea is simple. From idea to final output, Higgsfield gives you more control over the whole creative process. Whether you\'re making ads, social videos, product launches, cinematic clips, or full marketing'

[16:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'campaigns, this is one of the easiest platforms to start creating with AI. Try Higgsfield today using the link in the description below. The paper also goes through how AI was used for liver fibrosis. This is a condition where the'

[16:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'liver develops excessive scar tissue, usually from inflammation, and it can eventually lead to liver failure. The researchers asked the co-scientists to find new epigenetic targets for this'

[16:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'disease. In simple terms, epigenetics refers to the mechanisms that change how genes are turned on or off. Identifying these targets is like finding which specific switches in the DNA tell the'

[17:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'liver cells to produce excessive collagen and scar tissue and other stuff, which caused the fibrosis. So, once we identify these targets, it\'s easy to develop therapies that flip these switches back into a healthy'

[17:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'state. So, again, the AI system took this task and came up with a ton of hypotheses, debated with itself internally until it came up with a leaderboard of the best solutions. And it ultimately was able to identify new'

[17:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'epigenetic targets and proposed the drugs to hit them, including a drug called vorinostat. The breakthrough here is that vorinostat is already an FDA-approved drug. But it\'s actually used to treat a rare type of lymphoma'

[17:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cancer, not liver disease. So, again, the scientists tested the AI\'s theory in real life. And indeed, they found that vorinostat actually successfully reduced liver scarring without being toxic to'

[17:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'human liver cells. This is yet another example of a breakthrough discovery from this AI system. It shows that AI can accelerate the search for treatments by finding hidden potential in drugs we already know about. Drugs that are'

[18:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'currently used for completely different purposes. And it gets even crazier. So, let\'s discuss the third use case for this, which is antimicrobial resistance, or AMR for short. This is arguably one of the most severe global health threats'

[18:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of our century. Many common diseases like pneumonia, tuberculosis, or UTIs are caused by bacteria, fungi, and parasites. Now, we use drugs called antibiotics to kill them. But the'

[18:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'problem is that these can evolve over time to survive these drugs. Basically, the bacteria can adapt and become resistant to antibiotics and other treatments, meaning medicines designed today gradually lose their'

[18:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'effectiveness. Well, in this paper, by using Co Scientist, they were able to uncover a major discovery in how bacteria spread this antibiotic resistance. Here\'s more background on the problem. The researchers were trying'

[19:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to understand how antibiotic resistance spreads so quickly between completely different species of bacteria. So far we know that resistance is often carried in mobile genetic elements called CF PIC'

[19:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'eyes. These are like specialized packages that move from one bacterium to another. But usually these packages are very picky about which bacteria they enter. And what scientists don\'t fully'

[19:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'understand is how these CF PIC eyes were able to jump between different species so easily. Well, using Co-scientist researchers test the system to find the mechanism behind this. They just said,'

[19:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '"Hey, Co-scientist, here\'s a weird genetic element. Figure out how this bacterial gene transfer actually works." And in just two days of autonomous literature review and reflection and internal debate, Co-scientist generated'

[19:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a top-ranked hypothesis. It predicted that these CF PIC eyes actively interact with diverse phage tails. In really simple terms, these phage tails are essentially virus-like docking tools'

[20:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that latch onto and enter a host bacteria. The AI hypothesized that these CF PIC I genetic elements hijack the phage tails to dramatically expand the range of bacteria species it can infect.'

[20:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And that\'s why antimicrobial resistance can spread so quickly between different bacteria species. Again, keep in mind we didn\'t have this knowledge before. This is a completely new idea that the AI'

[20:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'deduced from its understanding of scientific literature. The remarkable thing is that the AI\'s theory actually perfectly matched the findings of an independent team of scientists who just figured it out in the lab after months'

[20:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of work. They haven\'t even published anything on it yet. In contrast, the AI was able to deduce all of this in just two days, which is crazy. This proves that the AI isn\'t just regurgitating information, it\'s actually coming up'

[21:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with completely new scientific ideas that work. Now, so far Co-scientist is pretty impressive, but it hits a limitation pretty quickly. So far, this can only synthesize information and come up with hypotheses. The next major step'

[21:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in AI science involves a system that can actually analyze the results once these ideas are tested in a lab and then iterate again and again. We need an AI system that can work alongside'

[21:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scientists as they do experiments and help them iterate further. Currently, scientists have to do a lot of the grunt lab work. It\'s messy and intensely physical. You need to gather evidence, pipette liquids, culture the cells, and'

[21:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'also write code to analyze a ton of raw data. All of this takes an immense amount of time, which is why most biology scientific papers takes months to years to publish. How can we get AI'

[21:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to automate these steps as well? So, that\'s where this next paper comes in. So, this is called a multi-agent system for automating scientific discovery, and this was also published in Nature in the'

[22:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'same week. Now, this is also an agentic system called Robin. But, here\'s where it differs from Google\'s Co-scientist. Co-scientist only focuses on the thinking part of discovery, but Robin is'

[22:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what they call a closed-loop system. It not only comes up with new ideas, but also interprets raw data from lab experiments to refine them in real time. So, this is an AI system that can manage'

[22:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the entire scientific cycle from start to finish and keep looping and iterating again and again to come up with new directions or dig deeper. Let\'s look under the hood of Robin. So, it relies on this system of specialized AI agents,'

[22:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but they each have very different roles. First, we have Crow, and its primary function is to perform accurate, concise literature review. So, it\'s like the researcher. If the human user asks a'

[22:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'question about a disease or something, Crow scans thousands of scientific papers to find quick summaries of how the disease works and which lab tests should be used to study it. Once a specific treatment or a drug is'

[23:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'suggested, the information is sent to the next agent called Falcon. It does a deep dive into the literature and writes a comprehensive report on that drug. It looks at its safety, how it works, and'

[23:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'potential risks. But, the true star of the Robin ecosystem and the agent that fundamentally distinguishes it from Co-scientist is the third agent called Finch. This is like the data analysis agent or the lab partner. After a human'

[23:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scientist tests the drugs in a lab, they just give the raw data to Finch, and Finch can then write its own code to analyze these numbers and create charts to see if the treatment actually worked.'

[23:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It autonomously writes, debugs, and executes code to analyze the raw, unstructured data that comes straight out from lab results, which is often the most brutal part of doing science. This is a huge distinction that we need to'

[23:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'emphasize. It\'s one thing for AI to read a published paper, which is already well-formatted with graphs and clearly written sections. It\'s entirely different and way more difficult to look at raw data from science experiments and'

[24:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'figure out what the hell is going on. It\'s notoriously messy and noisy, and it could be highly subjective. Two human scientists might look at the same data set and draw different conclusions, which makes it very prone to human error'

[24:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and subjective bias. So, how does Finch handle that? Well, the researchers building Robin knew that if they just asked a single instance of an AI model to analyze this messy data, it might fail or hallucinate something or make a'

[24:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bizarre subjective choice. So, to ensure accuracy, they gave Finch a fascinating architectural design. When it receives raw data, it doesn\'t just run Finch once. It actually launches eight'

[24:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'independent instances of the Finch agent to analyze the exact same data in parallel. It\'s like asking eight different research teams, and they all write their own code, they all clean the data their own way, and they all reach'

[25:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'their own conclusions. Then, the findings of these eight Finch agents are analyzed together using a consensus mechanism. In simple terms, the idea only gets accepted if the majority of the agents agree on it. In other words,'

[25:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'if at least 50% of these independent ideas reached the same conclusion. This process is super important because scientific data can be very messy and hard to interpret objectively. But, by'

[25:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'requiring a consensus, the system can output highly consistent and trustworthy results. The really cool thing about the design is that it\'s an endless loop. So, the findings from Finch can be fed back'

[25:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to the first crow agent to generate new hypotheses and figure out what to do next. It\'s an endless cycle. You can keep iterating again and again based on lab findings to eventually narrow down a solution for your specific problem. Now,'

